\par }\pard\plain \ql \li0\ri0\nowidctlpar\faauto\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs24\cf1\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\fs20\cf0 Each of the monster entries describes a typical creature of its kind. However, there are several met
hods by which extraordinary or unique monsters can be created using a typical creature as the foundation: by adding character classes, increasing a monster\rquote s Hit Dice, or by adding a template to a monster. These methods are not mutually exclusive
\emdash it\rquote s possible for a monster with a template to be improved by both increasing its Hit Dice and adding character class levels.
\par }{\b\fs20\cf0 Class Levels:}{\fs20\cf0  Intelligent creatures that are reasonably humanoid in shape most commonly advance by adding class levels. Creatures that fall into this category have an entry of \'93By character class\'94
 in their Advancement line. When a monster adds a class level, that level usually represents an increase in experience and learned skills and capabilities.
\par }{\b\fs20\cf0 Increased Hit Dice:}{\fs20\cf0  Intelligent creatures t
hat are not humanoid in shape, and nonintelligent monsters, can advance by increasing their Hit Dice. Creatures with increased Hit Dice are usually superior specimens of their race, bigger and more powerful than their run-of-the-mill fellows.
\par }{\b\fs20\cf0 Templates:}{\fs20\cf0  Bo
th intelligent and nonintelligent creatures with an unusual heritage or an inflicted change in their essential nature may be modified with a template. Templates usually result in tougher monsters with capabilities that differ from those of their common ki
n.
\par Each of these three methods for improving monsters is discussed in more detail below.
\par }{\fs36\cf0 
\par ABILITY SCORE ARRAYS
\par }{\fs20\cf0 Monsters are assumed to have completely average (or standard) ability scores\emdash a 10 or an 11 in each ability, as modified by their racial bonuses. H
owever, improved monsters are individuals and often have better than normal ability scores, and usually make use of either the elite array or the nonelite array of ability scores. Monsters who improve by adding a template, and monsters who improve by incr
easing their Hit Dice, may use any of the three arrays (standard, nonelite, or elite). Any monster unique enough to be improved could easily be considered elite.
\par }{\b\fs20\cf0 Elite Array: }{\fs20\cf0 The elite array is 15, 14, 13, 12, 10, 8. While the monster has one weakness compa
red to a typical member of its race, it is significantly better overall. The elite array is most appropriate for monsters who add levels in a player character class.
\par }{\b\fs20\cf0 Nonelite Array:}{\fs20\cf0  The nonelite array is 13, 12, 11, 10, 9, 8. The nonelite arr
ay does not necessarily make a monster better than normal, but it does customize the monster as an individual with strengths and weaknesses compared to a typical member of its race. The nonelite array is most appropriate for monsters who add class levels 
in a NPC class.
\par }{\b\fs20\cf0 Ability Score Improvement:}{\fs20\cf0  Treat monster Hit Dice the same as character level for determining ability score increases. This only applies to Hit Dice increases, monsters do not gain ability score increases for levels they \'93
already reached\'94 with their racial Hit Dice, since these adjustments are included in their basic ability scores.
\par }{\fs36\cf0 
\par MONSTERS AND CLASS LEVELS
\par }{\fs20\cf0 If a creature acquires a character class, it follows the rules for multiclass characters}{\i\fs20\cf0 .
\par }{\fs20\cf0 The creature\rquote s Hit Dice equal the number of class levels it has plus its racial Hit Dice. A creature\rquote s \'93monster class\'94
 is always a favored class, and the creature never takes XP penalties for having it. Additional Hit Dice gained from taking levels in a character class never affect a creature\rquote s size.
\par }{\b\fs20\cf0 Humanoids and Class Levels:}{\fs20\cf0 
 Creatures with 1 or less HD replace their monster levels with their character levels. The monster loses the attack bonus, saving throw bonuses, skills, and feats granted by its 1 monster HD and gains the attack bonus, save bonu
ses, skills, feats, and other class abilities of a 1st-level character of the appropriate class.
\par }{\b\fs20\cf0 Level Adjustment and Effective Character Level:}{\fs20\cf0  To determine the effective character level (ECL) of a monster character, add its level adjustment to its racial
 Hit Dice and character class levels. The monster is considered to have experience points equal to the minimum needed to be a character of its ECL. 
\par If you choose to equip a monster with gear, use its ECL as its character level for purposes of determining how much equipment it can purchase. Generally, only monsters with an Advancement entry of \'93By character class\'94
 receive NPC gear; other creatures adding character levels should be treated as monsters of the appropriate CR and assigned treasure, not equipment.
\par }{\b\fs20\cf0 Feat Acquisition and Ability Score Increases:}{\fs20\cf0  A monster\rquote s total Hit Dice, not its ECL, govern its acquisition of feats and ability score increases. 
\par }{\fs36\cf0 
\par INCREASING HIT DICE
\par }{\fs20\cf0 As its Hit Dice increase, a creature\rquote s attack bonuses and saving throw modifiers might improve. It gains more feats and skills, depending on its type, as shown on Table: Creature Improvement by Type.
\par Note that if a creature acquires a character class, it improves according to its class, not its type.
