\par }\pard\plain \ql \li0\ri0\nowidctlpar\faauto\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs24\cf1\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\fs20\cf0 Certain creatures are created by adding a template to an 
existing creature. A templated creature can represent a freak of nature, the individual creation of a single experimenter, or the first generation of offspring from parents of different species.
\par }{\cf0 
\par ACQUIRED AND INHERITED TEMPLATES
\par }{\fs20\cf0 Some templates can be added to creatures anytime. Templates such as these are referred to as acquired templates, indicating that the creature did not always have the attributes of the template.
\par Other templates, known as inherited templates, are part of a creature from the beginning of its existence. Creatures are born with these templates.
\par It\rquote s possible for a certain kind of template to be of either type. 
\par }{\cf0 
\par READING A TEMPLATE
\par }{\fs20\cf0 A template\rquote s description provides a set of instructions for altering an existing creature, known as the base creature. The changes that a template might cause to each line of a creature \rquote 
s statistics block are discussed below. Generally, if a template does not cause a change to a certain statistic, that entry is missing from the template description. For clarity,
 the entry for a statistic or attribute that is not changed is sometimes given as \'93Same as the base creature.\'94 
\par }{\b\fs20\cf0 Size and Type:}{\fs20\cf0  Templates often change a creature\rquote s type, and may change the creature\rquote s size.
\par If a template changes the base creature\rquote s type, the creature also acquires the augmented subtype unless the template description indicates otherwise. The augmented subtype is always paired with the creature\rquote 
s original type. Unless a template indicates otherwise, the new creature has the traits of the new type but the features of the original type.
\par If a template changes a creature\rquote s size, use Table: Changes to Statistics by Size to calculate changes to natural armor, Armor Class, attack rolls, and grapple bonus.
\par }{\b\fs20\cf0 Hit Dice and Hit Points:}{\fs20\cf0  Most templates do not change the number of Hit Dice a monster has, but some do. Some templates change the size of a creature\rquote 
s Hit Dice (usually by changing the creature type). A few templates change previously acquired Hit Dice, and continue to change Hit Dice gained with class levels, but most templates that change Hit Dice change only the creature\rquote 
s original HD and leave class Hit Dice unchanged.
\par If the Hit Dice entry in a template description is missing, Hit Dice and hit points do not change unless the creature\rquote s Constitution modifier changes.
\par }{\b\fs20\cf0 Initiative: }{\fs20\cf0 If a template changes the monster\rquote s Dexterity, or if it adds or removes the Improved Initiative feat, this entry changes.
\par }{\b\fs20\cf0 Speed:}{\fs20\cf0  If a template modifies a creature\rquote s speed, the template states how that happens. More commonly, a template adds a new movement mode.
\par }{\b\fs20\cf0 Armor Class:}{\fs20\cf0  If a template changes the creature\rquote s size, see Table: Changes to Statistics by Size to determine its new Armor Class and to see whether its natural armor changes. In some cases the method of determining A
rmor Class changes radically; the template description explains how to adjust the creature\rquote s AC.
\par }{\b\fs20\cf0 Base Attack/Grapple:}{\fs20\cf0  Templates usually do not change a creature\rquote s base attack bonus. If a template modifies a creature\rquote s base attack bonus, the template description states how that happens. Changes to a creature
\rquote s Strength score can change a creature\rquote s grapple bonus, as can changes to its size.
\par }{\b\fs20\cf0 Attack and Full Attack:}{\fs20\cf0  Most templates do not change a creature\rquote s attack bonus or modes of attack, even when the creature\rquote s type changes (the creature\rquote 
s base attack bonus is the same as a creature of the original type). Of course, any change in ability scores may affect attack bonuses. If Strength or Dexterity changes, use the new modifier to determine attack bonuses. A change in a monster\rquote 
s size also changes its attack bonus; see Table: Changes to Statistics by Size.
\par }{\b\fs20\cf0 Damage:}{\fs20\cf0  Damage changes with Strength. If the creature uses a two-handed weapon or has a single natural weapon, it adds 1-1/2 times its Strength bonus to the 
damage. If it has more than a single attack then it adds its Strength bonus to damage rolls for the primary attack and 1/2 its Strength bonus to all secondary attacks.
\par }{\b\fs20\cf0 Space/Reach:}{\fs20\cf0  A template may change this entry if it changes the monster\rquote s size. Note that this table does not take into account special situations such as exceptional reach.
\par }{\b\fs20\cf0 Special Attacks:}{\fs20\cf0  A template may add or remove special attacks. The template description gives the details of any special attacks a template provides, including how to determine saving throw DCs, if applicable.
\par }{\b\fs20\cf0 Special Qualities:}{\fs20\cf0  A template may add or remove special qualities. The template description gives the details of any special qualities a template provides, including how to determine saving throw DCs, if applicable. 
Even if the special qualities entry is missing from a template description, the creature still gains any qualities associated with its new type.
\par }{\b\fs20\cf0 Base Saves:}{\fs20\cf0  As with attacks, changing a monster\rquote s type does not always change its base saving throw bonuses. Yo
u only need to adjust them for new modifiers for Constitution, Dexterity, or Wisdom. A template may, however, state that a monster has a different \'93good\'94 saving throw.
\par }{\b\fs20\cf0 Abilities:}{\fs20\cf0  If a template changes one or more ability scores, these changes are noted here.
\par }{\b\fs20\cf0 Skills: }{\fs20\cf0 As with attacks, changing a monster\rquote s type does not always change its skill points. Most templates don\rquote t change the number of Hit Dice a creature has, so you don\rquote 
t need to adjust skills in that case unless the key abilities for those skills have changed, or the template gives a bonus on one or more skills, or unless the template gives a feat that provides a bonus on a skill check. 
\par Some templates change how skill points are determined, but this change usually only affects skill points gained after the template is applied. Treat skills listed in the base creature\rquote 
s description as class skills, as well as any new skills provided by the template. 
\par }{\b\fs20\cf0 Feats:}{\fs20\cf0  Since most templates do not change the number of Hit Dice a creature has, a template will not change the number of feats the creature has. Some templates grant one or more bonus feats.
\par }{\b\fs20\cf0 Environment:}{\fs20\cf0  Usually the same as the base creature.
\par }{\b\fs20\cf0 Organization:}{\fs20\cf0  Usually the same as the base creature.
\par }{\b\fs20\cf0 Challenge Rating:}{\fs20\cf0  Most templates increase the creature\rquote s Challenge Rating. A template might provide a modifier to be added to the base creature\rquote 
s CR, or it might specify a range of modifiers depending on the base creature\rquote s original Hit Dice or CR.
\par }{\b\fs20\cf0 Treasure: }{\fs20\cf0 Usually the same as the base creature.
\par }{\b\fs20\cf0 Alignment:}{\fs20\cf0  Usually the same as the base creature, unless the template is associated with a certain alignment.
\par }{\b\fs20\cf0 Advancement:}{\fs20\cf0  Usually the same as the base creature.
\par }{\b\fs20\cf0 Level Adjustment:}{\fs20\cf0  This entry is a modifier to the base creature\rquote s level adjustment. Any level adjustment
 is meaningless unless the creature retains a high enough Intelligence (minimum 3) to gain class levels after applying the template.
\par }{\cf0 
\par }{\fs21\cf0 Adding More Than One Template
\par }{\fs20\cf0 In theory, there\rquote s no limit to the number of templates you can add to a creature. To add mor
e than one template, just apply each template one at a time. Always apply inherited templates before applying acquired templates. Whenever you add multiple templates, pay attention to the creature\rquote s type\emdash 
you may add a template that makes the creature ineligible for other templates you might want to add.
\par }{\fs36\cf0 
\par ADVANCED MONSTER CHALLENGE RATING
\par }{\fs20\cf0 When adding class levels to a creature with 1 or less HD, you advance the creature like a character. Otherwise, use the following guidelines.
\par }{\cf0 
\par ADDING CLASS LEVELS
\par }\pard\plain \s15\ql \li0\ri0\nowidctlpar\faauto\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {If you are advancing a monster by adding player character class levels, decide if the class levels directly improve the monster
\rquote s existing capabilities.
\par }\pard\plain \ql \li0\ri0\nowidctlpar\faauto\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs24\cf1\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\fs20\cf0 When adding class levels to a creature, you should give it typical ability scores appropriate for that class. Mo
st creatures are built using the standard array of ability scores: 11, 11, 11, 10, 10, 10, adjusted by racial modifiers. If you give a creature a PC class use the elite array of ability scores before racial adjustments: 15, 14, 13, 12, 10, 8. Creatures wi
th NPC classes use the nonelite array of 13, 12, 11, 10, 9, 8. T
\par }{\fs21\cf0 
\par Associated Class Levels
\par }{\fs20\cf0 Class levels that increase a monster\rquote s existing strengths are known as associated class levels. Each associated class level a monster has increases its CR by 1.
\par Barbarian, fighter, paladin, and ranger are associated classes for a creature that relies on its fighting ability.
\par Rogue and ranger are associated classes for a creature that relies on stealth to surprise its foes, or on skill use to give itself an advantage. 
\par A spellcasting class is an associated class for a creature that already has the ability to cast spells as a character of the class in question, since the monster\rquote s levels in the spellcasting class stack with its innate spellcasting ability.
\par }{\fs21\cf0 
\par Nonassociated Class Levels
\par }{\fs20\cf0 If you add a class level that doesn\rquote t directly play to a creature\rquote s strength the class level is considered nonassociated, and things get a little more complicated}{\i\fs20\cf0 . }{\fs20\cf0 
Adding a nonassociated class level to a monster increases its CR by 1/2 pe
r level until one of its nonassociated class levels equals its original Hit Dice. At that point, each additional level of the same class or a similar one is considered associated and increases the monster\rquote s CR by 1.
\par Levels in NPC classes are always treated as nonassociated.
\par }{\cf0 
\par ADDING HIT DICE
\par }{\fs20\cf0 When you improve a monster by adding Hit Dice, use Table: Improved Monster CR Increase to determine the effect on the creature\rquote s CR. Keep in mind that many monsters that advance by adding Hit Dice also increase in size. 
Do not stack this CR increase with any increase from class levels. In general, once you\rquote ve doubled a creature\rquote 
s CR, you should closely watch any additional increases in its abilities. Adding Hit Dice to a creature improves several of its abilities, and radical increases might not follow this progression indefinitely. Compare the monster\rquote 
s improved attack bonus, saving throw bonuses, and any DCs of its special abilities from the HD increase to typical characters of the appropriate level and adjust the CR accordingly.
